title: Yarra Ranges National Park - Moths
description: Mt Donna Buang is located in the Yarra Ranges National Park and has a diverse moth population within the cool temperate rainforest habitat.

items.title: Acronictinae spp.
items.content_text: The current accepted name in the Australian Faunal Directory is Acronictinae however the synonym is (Xanthoptera) macrosema.

items.title: Stathmopoda spp.
items.content_text: Typical resting position.

items.title: Nola vernalis
items.content_text: Second image included as one fo the tufts can be seen in the lateral view - on the left forewing near shoulder.

items.title: Palaeosia sp. (2)
items.content_text: For record only.

items.title: Dissomorphia australiaria
items.content_text: A bit ragged but a useful record.

items.title: Epyaxa subidaria
items.content_text: This particularly dark specimen is quite different to the lighter forms.

items.title: Poecilasthena pellucida
items.content_text: A worn specimen but there for the record. p.s. the cover for MoV3 shows a better specimen photographed further down the road towards Warburton.

items.title: Glaucocharis dilatella
items.content_text: Not a clear image but OK for the record.

items.title: Hednota opulentellus
items.content_text: Hednota opulentellus

items.title: Furcatrox australis
items.content_text: Furcatrox australis

items.title: Orvasca sp. (1)
items.content_text: Species (1) as per Moths of Victoria Part 2

items.title: Cosmaresta spp.
items.content_text: This belongs to a complex of similar white moths with black patterns belonging to the genus Cosmaresta.

items.title: Scoparia spp.
items.content_text: This specimen may be S. plagiotis but there appear to be a number of differences and this identification will need to be confirmed or corrected.

items.title: Poecilasthena sp. (2)
items.content_text: As per Moths of Victoria Part 3.

items.title: Rhuma spp.
items.content_text: Scales on forewings worn.  This species appears to inhabit cool temperate forest gullies in Vic.

items.title: Chrysolarentia pantoea
items.content_text: Chrysolarentia pantoea was listed in Australian and world Checklist but has since been removed from Chrysolarentia; it remains unallocated to genus at time of posting.

items.title: Cyclotorna spp.
items.content_text: Cyclotorna sp.

items.title: Nola crucigera
items.content_text: One of several on sheet.

items.title: Cryptophasa rubescens
items.content_text: Light coloured form on same sheet as Cathy.

items.title: Scopula spp.
items.content_text: Scopula sp. (1) in MoV 3.

items.title: Endoxyla interlucens
items.content_text: There is some confusion about the name interlucens which may be a more northern species.

items.title: Endoxyla spp.
items.content_text: This is also the female of the Undescribed species however there is a major loss of scales on the wings.  It gives the appearance of brown colour and you can see the wing veins clearly.  There is also some damage around the head area.  Surprising she could still navigate.

items.title: Endoxyla spp.
items.content_text: This is the female of the undescribed species (same date and location).

items.title: Endoxyla spp.
items.content_text: This is an undescribed species.

items.title: Paraterpna sp. (1)
items.content_text: Species 1 as per Moths of Victoria Part 4

items.title: Asthenoptycha spp.
items.content_text: Very similar to Asthenoptycha iriodes.

items.title: Xenomusa monoda
items.content_text: This genus is in Ennominae - no tribe assigned.

items.title: Maxates centrophylla
items.content_text: Scale loss but still beautiful.

items.title: Chrysolarentia sp. (2)
items.content_text: Species 2 according to Moths of Victoria Part 3.

items.title: Nataxa flavescens
items.content_text: One egg on the sheet near this female.  Shadow removed from beneath left forewing to make it more obvious.  Moth was very restless - obviously not the expected place to lay eggs.
